PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:Market Tone: Cautious ahead of Bernanke press conference. Dollar mixed, Treasurys lower, oil slightly higher, gold little changedOvernight Action: BP Net Profit Rises; S&P Changes Japan Outlook to Negative;Watch for: Fed rate decision and press conference,  earnings from Ebay, Starbucks, Boeing, ConocoPhillipsThe Breakfast BriefingToday, all eyes will go to the Bearded One.Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke will face the scribes in a first-ever press conference at 2:15 p.m. EDT. The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. The Fed-funds futures sees only a 26% chance that the Fed will raise rates to 0.5% by next February.As investors fidget about what the Bearded One might say, earnings will come in full force once again. On Tuesday, strong earnings from 3M, Ford Motor, Delta Air Lines and UPS helped set a robust tone from the opening bell.The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 115.49 to 12595.37, its highest close since June 5, 2008. The Nasdaq Composite jumped 21.66 to 2847.54, its highest close since Oct. 31, 2007. And the S&P 500 gained 11.99 to 1347.24, its best close since June 17, 2008.On Wednesday, earnings will come from all directions, with energy and aerospace dominating.On the energy front, Baker Hughes, Cabot Oil & Gas, BP, ConocoPhillips, ENI, Hess Corp. and National Oil Well Varco report. Energy companies have reported strong earnings, boosted by rising oil prices. Boeing, General Dynamics and Northrop Grumman report on the aerospace side. Lockheed Martin reported solid earnings Tuesday; its shares rose more than 2%.Other notable earnings: Norfolk Southern, Whirlpool, Las Vegas Sands, Akamai, Baidu, Dr. Pepper Snapple, Green Mountain Coffee Roasters, eBay, Credit Suisse, Southern Co., and Barrick Gold. (A fuller list of key earnings due today are down below.)On the economic front, March durable goods orders are expected to show a 2.4% gain, reversing an unexpected decline in February. Also, the Energy Department reports petroleum data mid-morning. Crude oil stocks are expected to rise 1.1 million barrels and gasoline stocks are expected to decline once again. (A complete list of G7 economic reports due on Wednesday is at the end of this post.)The market surge on Tuesday had some chin-scratchers arguing that investors were buying the rumor (Bernanke will be really soft/nice/kind/luvy-duvy) in anticipation of selling that news (the actual statement/press briefing). PARAGRAPH.#text: SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones)--Mercury emissions are on the rise from older U.S. coal-fired power plants, according to a study released Thursday. Fifty coal-fired power plants in Texas, Pennsylvania, Alabama, Georgia and eight other states produced more emissions of mercury in 2007 than they did the previous year, according to the study, by the Washington-based Environmental Integrity Project. Together, the plants emitted 20 tons of mercury in 2007. #text: Ameritech (AIT)

Headlines.Headline: Lower returns on the horizon

#text:
Investors will have to rethink returns from U.S. stocks this year,
    according to one leading fund manager. "In 1998 we are entering a different investing
    environment than the one we have been in for most of the last 15 years," said
president,

, in an interview
    with Reuters. From 1982 to 1997 returns averaged roughly 19 percent a year. Miller sees
    them dropping to between eight and 10 percent this year. "The strategies needed in
    the new environment are very different" explains Miller, who also manages Legg
    mason's Value
    Fund

    'em." He cited Columbia/HCA

HealthCare, under U.S. federal investigation for possible Medicare fraud, which he hopes

    projected to return 8 to 10 percent "you can start off at five to seven percent on
    yield, then you don't need very much on capital gains to beat the market.''

    analysts' expectations. Sales of the company's software -- which allows businesses to
    automate human resource and accounting operations -- increased 76 percent to $260.6
    million over the same period a year ago. The Pleasanton, Calif.-based company said it
    expects to increase sales by the same rate during the current quarter. Operating margins
    for the current quarter are expected to come in below 18 percent, as is typical in the
    seasonally weak period. But PeopleSoft said it will maintain its usual 18 to 20 percent
    operating margin for the entire year.
